We have some new little babies available for adoption. These 3 boys and their siblings were rescued from a feeder breeder tonight. The “unwanted” ones as they put it. 😞 

They’re so sweet and deserve a good home. I’ll post the others maybe tomorrow if I have time. 😬 

I won’t ever buy these rescue rats from a feeder breeder btw, but if they’re willing to surrender them I will always take them in. Otherwise, they kill them and potentially just throw them away…it’s the sad reality for rats, they’re so easily discarded. My understanding is that this person doesn’t feed these hairless looking ones to their reptiles, so they get rid of them. And sometimes if the rats are lucky enough, they look for a rescue to take them. They’ve been contacting me every few months for the past year or so. 💔😞

This was not what I expected to find when I went into the Guinea pig room this afternoon…two wet newborns! 😭 Remember the 4 Guinea pigs I got from the shelter 7 weeks and 2 days ago…? Well…someone WAS pregnant. And now I’m on high alert because there are 2 more females who may be pregnant too! I thought we got lucky…but they must have gotten pregnant just DAYS before they were rescued. 😭 

Sooo, ugh. Idk. I’m just bummed, I wasn’t expecting this anymore. One of the females is a baby herself…one is a teen, and one is an adult. 😞 (I believe it was the adult who gave birth so far). Please pray for the other 2 younger girls to make it through safely if they do give birth. We will also probably need one more Guinea pig cage AT LEAST. 

🌟Background…these Guinea pigs came in to the shelter as a group of 5. The shelter sexed them as 1 adult male, and 4 females. I was asked if I could help with the females in case they were pregnant. I picked them up right away, brought them home and realized immediately that one of the little babies was actually a boy. So the “females” had been separated from the adult male, but kept with a young male by mistake. 😣 I did let the volunteers know at the shelter that one of the piggies was misgendered and it was brought to the attention of the shelter staff and suggested that they are trained better on sexing piggies so this doesn’t happen again. 😢

This may be long…but a lot of the reason why I’ve been personally struggling this year has been due to the cost of rescuing as many animals as I do… It’s been extremely stressful and expensive, I’ve struggled to keep up with my credit card payments due to so many costs for the kittens this year especially. We had so many who needed extra eye removal surgeries, which never received enough donations to help pay for them all, but they all got done. It’s all just piling up, and it’s led to me falling deeper into depression because it’s a lot for one person to handle. I went back to school full time, hoping to get into a job eventually that can help me pay for my rescue. But that has also been a struggle because I’m so busy with the kittens and other animals, while battling depression and anxiety, that I barely have time for anything else…let alone my own son even. 

And I’ve also realized it’s just a pipedream, so I’m at a stalemate, unsure what to do if I can’t get this under control. 😣  My problem is, I don’t like asking for help, when I know everyone is struggling the same way I am. 

But if you could spare $5 (or more if you’re able) to help us get caught up, it would really make a difference. 🙏🏼 

I think most rescuers must battle these same or similar thoughts and issues in some way, compassion fatigue is very draining and it’s been weighing on me heavily since last year… I can’t/don’t want to quit, but I’m struggling.

So I recently wanted to set up my bed-desk again, but to do that I had to move the boxes I put between my bed and the wall that Hercules used to use to get down off the Kitty Kasa beds in the corner. So he has to learn how to get down from a new height/spot, which is a process. 😅

He was sleeping on the desk (all the cats love sleeping there), he can climb up no-problem. But if he can’t reach down and touch something with his paw, if it’s new he has no idea if there’s a floor underneath or if he will just fall forever 😬. So he’s very cautious about stepping down, especially since he doesn’t jump. 😊 I was trying to show him that there was something down there, but after 10 minutes I just ended up holding him by the armpits and helping him place his paws onto the bed below, so he felt on his own while still standing on the desk, that something WAS there. Maybe next time he will be a little more brave and do it himself! 😬 🥰

Hercules learns very fast, if you’ve seen the video I posted of him climbing to the ceiling on the super high cat tower, and onto the wall climbers…you’ll understand he adapts very easily. He figured that out all on his own when no one was around. But when he’s struggling right in front of me and crying for help, I help him figure it out or he might be up there all day haha. He’s fully capable of navigating just about anywhere he can reach. And he can get off of my bed onto the floor easily because I have a platform bed and it has a ledge, so he figured out he can step on the ledge and trusts to hop (fall) down to the floor and lands on his feet 98% of the time. He’s unstoppable 😂 💪🐱 

I get messages asking how Hercules is every so often, he’s great. 😊 He’s just a normal cat basically, with a few quirks. But he doesn’t require any special care despite having several disabilities. I don’t know why no one ever wanted to adopt him, he’s a cool cat and it’s amazing to watch him figure out life and adjust. I’ve had people tell me how sad it is that he is blind and deaf (and tbh I can’t even begin to imagine that struggle), but he doesn’t let it stop him, he survived in a warehouse until he was rescued around 8 weeks old. Idk how. 🤷🏼‍♀️💗

Yikes…it’s what I suspected, Ralph had some ingrown nails. 😭😭 His paws are so tight with extra claws, and he doesn’t easily allow his foster dad to check his feet, so this was unexpected. Ralph is an ex-feral kitten that we rescued at 5 months old, him and his siblings were found curled up on top of their dead sibling’s body, his brother Bart survived FIP and his sibling Lucky was rescued in severe liver failure but passed away at the vet (Ralph is now 1 yr 7 months old), he’s still a bit wary of being touched in certain ways, though he is very friendly now since he’s been fostered for over a year. 

The second picture shows the nails that were embedded in the pad, the dr said his nails are not growing in a typical way even for a polydactyl, so they are prone to growing into the pad. My cat Ariel has tons of extra toes, but this never happens to her at all so we just assumed it wasn’t happening to Ralph and his brother (it’s not happening with his brother Bart, Bart is like Ariel where his nails grow “normally” for a polydactyl). 

The vet was able to cut the nails and remove the embedded claws 😭, soak the paw and clean it up, gave him a shot of convenia (antibiotic), and sending him home with gabapentin for pain. 

I feel horrible that this happened, & his foster dad feels like shit because he didn’t notice it sooner. 😢

Feral mama is still taking great care of her 5 babies. 💗 I realized after that I didn’t get a better picture of the white and orange one, but he’s there. 😂 

They’re so big already! 5 weeks old tomorrow. 💗 Mama is still pretty “feral”, although I did have a “moment” with her…idk if it was something in the air or what, but she was purring one night, rubbing the cage bars and let me pet her. I have cried many tears over this cat, I have videos of her being sweet to me…and having to send her back to the street is just heartbreaking. 💔 She’s never once attacked me, she lets me grab her babies right in front of her, she’s swatted at me through the cage but not really with claws, she hisses but has never bitten me when I open the door and take the bowl while she’s literally touching me trying to get past me to get out (lol). 

The hardest part is having a strange bond with the “feral” cats I care for temporarily, even if they don’t “like” me, I still care about them and I hate that I feel like I’ll be failing her when I send her away. I’ve seen her friendly side so it haunts me..the “what-ifs”. 😞

Nina is still resting after her surgery. She finally started nibbling on some hay a little bit ago. 😮‍💨 It can be really scary if they don’t start eating right away because rabbits need to have access to food constantly to keep their digestive system moving. If they don’t eat within 12-24 hours, their body can shut down and go into “GI stasis”, which they can die from within 1-2 days. Rabbits are so delicate 😰

Nina is honestly the perfect bunny. I’m not entirely sure why she was listed as “undersocialized”, she is sweet as can be. Super easy to handle (most bunnies don’t like being picked up — but Nina does!), easy to clip her nails even if you’re a beginner and have to go slow (she’s patient), she comes to you for attention, and she deserves everything in the world after what she’s been through. 💗 She will be available for adoption soon (if I can manage to let her go 🥹). 

PS. Nina’s eyes sometimes look pink and sometimes look blue. 😂 Shes perfect.

Devore kitties update. So, mama Italia (not pictured) is okay, she is not sick as we were worried about at first with the drooling. She only has horrible diarrhea (parasites) and is being treated. 

However, mama Alexina (#A777235) was just starting to get sick when we got her out of Devore shelter. She has a clogged nose and sneezing, and is not really eating much at all anymore so she started an appetite stimulant today. Only one of her babies has been in critical condition. They are all on antibiotics and are improving. The sick newborn is still strong, he’s still drinking milk, I just have to keep his face cleaned of any discharge. Frequently his nose and mouth will be slimed shut with sticky fluidy discharge (boogers and mucus from the mouth). I’m hopeful he will pull through still, the whole family are also getting nebulizer treatments 2-3x a day to help clear the airways. 

I’m glad we got them when we did, the newborns would not have lasted long at the shelter with this virus. Especially without immediate antibiotic treatment and specialized care.

Hi guys! Two of our mama kitties (including sweet mama Daisy) have tested positive for FIV. Not a big deal though!! And ALL of their kittens will be tested to confirm they did not inherit this infectious disease. (I’ve had FIV+ moms before and it’s never been transferred to their kittens via milk exchange in my experiences, but we always check and don’t assume). 

FYI. 📢This does not mean she is not adoptable!📢 She is very adoptable! Daisy is a very very sweet, young, and well mannered kitty. So as long as your other kitties are friendly too, it will be fine (if you have other kitties!). She will just have a lowered immune system, but she will otherwise be fine and can live a normal life. 💗 #fivpositive 

Check out the @supportfiv account for more information on FIV! Consider giving an FIV+ kitty a home, they are usually unwanted due to fear. 😢
